column313: I tried to think of how best to deal with the Asset A ramdomization factor. I saw that a lot of the time when there would be a number that was lower than zero it would follow another one less than zero.

I almost always went with 40% A 60% B. this seemed to give a constant positive outcome with fairly good results. If I began to fall lower than 4 dollars i became more agressive and took more risks. If I was ever over $10 i became less agressive and would do a larger percentage of B. If my end result was dismal (1.50) or less  I would buy asset C
Tried to make reasonable decision that were not too risky. If I got too low  I invested all in A to try to get the money back.

I made my decisions by taking bigger risks when I had less money  and smaller risks when I had more money because I did not want to lose it all. I also took bigger risks at the beginning and less risks towards the end of each path. I also tried my best to predict if the next multiplier for A would be bigger or smaller and allocate amounts to A accordingly in comparison to B to try and make the most money possible.
It was fun I really enjoyed it. I took big risks at the beginning and then made more conservative investments as I earned more money.

I feel that I did not develop a good strategy for investing. I felt mostly subject to luck during the paths  and this was frustrating. Perhaps there was something that I did not pick up on about how to invest effectively.
I ususally invested most of my money into asset A because in the long run the average interest rate is higher.
i was fairly conservative most of the time  but sometimes took a chance when i felt like it. when investments were declining  i tended to invest more money in A instead of B.

Bet more when losing. Go back to 50/50 when winning. Tried going for the while cats sometimes by betting a lot on A or buying C as long as money was allowed  but failed miserably  judging from the result  which led to using the first strategy again.
Exciting! I can understand all the parts. Experience in judging previous results can help predict a little bit in the next decision. But it still bases a little bit on luck.
